\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Linear Advection Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest initial-value problem (IVP) is given by the first-order partial
 differential equation (PDE) with a constant coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{u}{t}+a\pdv{u}{x}=0\qc t>0\qc x\in(-\infty,\infty)
\]

\end_inset

and the initial condition (IC)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(t=0,x)=u_{0}(x)\qc x\in(-\infty,\infty)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The PDE is only meaningful in smooth regions.
 However, if we let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi:=u\qc\vec{f}:=f(u)\vu{e}_{x}\qc f(u):=au
\]

\end_inset

we can write it as a conservation law
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{u}{t}+\pdv{f}{x}=0
\]

\end_inset

for which a weak solution that contains discontinuities is allowed, as long
 as the weak solution satisfies the jump condition at discontinuities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The characteristic curve of the PDE passing through 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{0},x_{0})$
\end_inset

 is the solution of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{x}{t}=a\qc x(t=0)=x_{0}
\]

\end_inset

which is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=at+x_{0}
\]

\end_inset

If we treat 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 as a varying parameter, then all of the characteristic curves together
 form a one-parameter family of parallel straight lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 plane.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The characteristic curves of the linear advection equation are straight
 lines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Along any characteristic curve, the rate of change of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{u}{t}=\pdv{u}{t}+\dv{x}{t}\pdv{u}{x}=0
\]

\end_inset

which means 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 remains constant along a characteristic curve.
 The solution of the IVP is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(t,x)=u_{0}(x_{0})=u_{0}(x-at)
\]

\end_inset

The physical meaning of this solution is a wave packet moving with constant
 speed 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, whose shape keeps unchanged.
 This is why it is called the 
\noun on
linear advection equation
\noun default
 or the 
\noun on
single wave equation
\noun default
.
\end_layout

